description.text:
The reason I built this is because its is about 10 times expensive to 3d print the nema mount, as compared to a laser cut acrylic.  
Using the attached .dxf file, you can create 4 pieces for the 4 faces of a mount, and then using interlocking joints +epoxy, construct the mount.

Created in Inkscape, Use 7mm Acrylic or metal.The triangular support is provided as single, but you need to make two.No need to flip, or mirror, just cut as is. The square border around the shaft hole for the motor is to be etched, not cut. The design has been optimised for use with 7mm acrylic.
If you choose a thinner acrylic, it would be fine, but it would not be able to hold the weight of the motor+the belt tension on the shaft. Using an acrylic thicker than 7mm will be ideal, but there could be gaps in the joints, which help in gluing the mount. The vertical slots on the bottom plate are 4.2mm wide and 30mm long. The distance between their centers is 30mm. The motor mounting holes are 3mm in diameter, and the shaft hole is 22.5mm in diameter. The interlocking joints are 7mm long, and 5mm wide.

title: Extruder Cold End 40mm Fan Shroud for Monoprice Maker Select v2.1

description.text:
This is a fan shroud for the extruder's cold end on a Monoprice Maker Select v2.1 (and Wanhao Duplicator i3, and probably others). I designed it to provide these benefits:

  • Redirect all air from the cold end heatsink upwards and away from the print
  • Protect fan blades from fingers/tools
  • Take the place of those little black fan spacers that are impossible to install
  • Make it easier to align and reinstall the cold end fan and heatsink

I also made it big enough to hold a Noctua 40mm fan, which is a little thicker and wider than the standard 40x40x10mm dimensions due to the built in rubber isolators.

Other mods

This Thing is part of a set of mods I've designed for this printer - here's the rest of the set, I hope you find them useful:

  • Heated bed stabilizers
  • Bracket for Thorped's fan duct

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select v2.1

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

Doesn't matter

Notes:

Should print without supports on an FDM printer.

1. Remove the screws holding on the extruder cold end fan, fan spacers, and heat sink.
    • Set the spacers aside - they will not be reused.
    • The extruder stepper motor is loose at this point, so don't bump it.
  2. Insert the cold end fan into the top slot of the fan shroud.
  3. Press the heat sink into the large opening of the fan shroud, fins toward the fan.
    • If you haven't already, take this opportunity to put a little thermal grease on the lower 1cm of the heat sink, where it touches the cooling block of the hot end.
  4. Insert the screws you removed in step 1 through the holes in the fan shroud, the bottom holes of the fan, and the bottom holes of the heat sink.
  5. Carefully reattach the fan shroud + fan + heatsink to the extruder stepper.

Designed in DesignSpark Mechanical.

title: Filament Funnel For Frustration-Free Feeding Customizer

description.text:
I was tweaking my Filament Funnel for Frustration-Free Feeding (6F) when I realized that I'd designed the thing to fit my own filament tubes with my own filament, and wouldn't work with other tube or filament diameters. Since I designed it in OpenSCAD anyway, I figured I'd just upload it and let you change whatever you want. This is my first time trying to do this, so let me know what you think.

This is a guide to make it much easier to load filament into tiny holes in tubes. One end slips over the tube, and the other has a sloped funnel that leads the filament into its hole. My eyesight and digital dexterity aren't so good, and my filament holders face a wall. I had to stand bent awkwardly to get the end of the filament near the hole, and I used to scream in frustration after the tenth failed attempt to jam the damned thing in. More often that not a failure would mean dropped filament snapping back around the spool. What a pain in the ass! The 6F has made my life so much easier. I hope it's useful to others as well.

title: Simple wall light from Tween Light RGB LED strips

description.text:
A simple minimalist wall light made of Tween Light RGB LED strips. These strips are normally made for backlighting TVs and have a handy remote so you don't need to install a switch.
The strips make for a nice reading light with almost no shadows. When you need to be awake, use the white light, but if you are going to bed, you can switch off the blue light to help you get sleepy. Of course, mood lighting is also a possibility :)
I bought these strips in Bauhaus, you can see the packaging in the third picture, but they are also available unbranded and cheaper in webstores.

Printer:

Heavily modded Craftbot

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm or less

Infill:

20% or less

Notes:

Any 3D-printer should work, this is an easy print.
Print one of each model.
If you orient the models properly (largest holes upwards), no supports are needed.
Print using any material that works for you, I did it in PLA. The prints do not need to be strong, the strips are quite light.

You will need a hot glue gun or some superglue.

  1. Take two strips and a short connector lead, assemble them into the left holder, taking care that the ends of strips are aligned, but the strips are facing in opposite directions. Glue the cover on the left holder above the connector lead. Do the same for the right holder.
  2. Disassemble the controller box in the Tween Light package and take out the controller PCB.
  3. Screw the middle holder box on the wall.
  4. Put the connectors in the holes in the left side of the box so they will be supported by the box and properly connected to the strips, but will not take up space inside the box. Screw the left holder with the two strips on the wall in the right place. Do the same for the right holder. You should have the light already mostly built now.
  5. Solder or otherwise connect the connectors to the PCB, the wires are clearly marked. Since you already have the connector lead in the side holders, you only need to connect one strip on each side.
  6. Position the PCB with the power supply receptacle above the hole for the power supply plug, threading the remote receiver out of the larger hole. Glue the PCB in place. Glue on the box cover. Connect the power supply.

My idea is to lock/unlock the lead screws with GCODE M355 command, formerly fot case light but you can use it for this project too, using one free pin on my RAMPS and a relay for Arduino.   • a 2mm pim
  • an Arduino relay like this

The bases I uploaded are for 3030 and 2020/2040 (V)rails.

This is a simple wedge with a lip. You use it after chilling when you are transferring wort to a fermentation chamber. It tips your kettle slightly to help condense the trub and reduce wort wastage.
I also use it at bottling in the same way - I transfer the fermented beer into a separate bottling vessel for bulk priming so this lets me again reduce sediment transfer and reduce wastage. These are a good size for 15 litre vessels as I brew 10 litre / 2 gallon batches - if you gear is larger they may or may not work - just make them as big as you can on your printer. There are four different tilts to try - I am still deciding which works best when.

hot wort is dangerous as it sticks to you meaning it burns your skin better as contact is longer - this thing is no way safe to balance 10 litres of boiling wort on.

Description

This is a tool to reduce the length of Armattan standoff used on elevenQuad Onix 111 frame from 24mm to 22mm.

The standoff is an M3 with output diameter of 4mm, available here : https://www.armattanproductions.com/pages/hardware_details/35/47

What you need

  • M6 screw, length and head does not matter
  • M3 screw, length and head does not matter
  • A file
  • A caliper

Instruction

  1. Print the part in the same position as the STL
  2. Screw few mm of the M6 screw in the biggest hole (be careful to not brake the printed thread) and insert the standoff (picture 2)
  3. Play with the screw to have only 1 mm going out on top (picture 3)
  4. File the standoff until the top of printed part (picture 4 and 5)
  5. Remove the standoff with M3 screw (picture 6)
  6. Clean up dust in the tool by removing M6 screw, this will avoid scratches on the standoff
  7. Measure the standoff, it should be around 23mm length. Your measure -22mm will be the length you will need to remove in the other side of the standoff
  8. Insert the standoff in the printed part with the non filled side out of the printed part
  9. Repeat step 3 and 4 with the adequate
  10. You should now have a standoff length of 22mm (picture 7). Tip: better to have a bit shorter than longer

description.text:
CAUTION: If you are using the stock bearing sandwich idlers on the front, you will need to add an extra slightly smaller washer underneath the 1st big washer.

The gantry of the X5s is pretty wobbly, due to the short wheel base on the brackets and the lack of fixture support on the x rail. Fortunately, the X5s has quite a lot of spare rail hidden away at the front, and the only thing in the way is the X end stop!

By redesigning the X endstop bracket, I was able to extend the wheel base by twice the original, from 45mm to 90mm, and it makes a heck of a difference. The gantry is so rigid now, that it was pretty clear my whole frame was slightly skewed, and I was able to use the assembled gantry as a guide to re-square my frame.

It also has mega solid braces for the x-bar, mounting at 4 points each side on 2 planes, for ultimate alignment and stiffness.

The new X endstop design also removes the need for some silly extra spacer on the bed for the Z endstop, it is now positioned to just touch the frame of the bed.

I will get round to a more detailed parts and instructions list, but for now you can reuse most of the stock boltrs, you will need an extra;

8x 5mm washer (no wheel spacers required, but does need a 1mm washer)
2x M5 x 50 bolt (for the idler pulleys)
4x M3 x 30 bolts (for the back side braces)
4x v-slot nut things (for the back side braces, don't know the correct name for them)

Print as already oriented in the STL files, no supports needed.

I will also be uploading my e3d-v6 mount soon shown in the pictures, that combines a belt straighter for the 2 very unaligned belts on the extruder.

title: GUST - i3 print cooler (Plus, v2.1, maybe others?)

description.text:
TL;DR

GUST is a high-efficiency part-cooling fan shroud for the i3 family of printers, designed based on the results of my print cooling experiments. It meets five design criteria:

  1. Dump as much cold air as possible, at the highest pressure possible, as close to the nozzle as possible. This improves the quality of short layers.
  2. Do not trap hot air in the plastic deposition area. Push it away so that warping is reduced.
  3. Allow easy access to the nozzle for bed levelling.
  4. Provide a clear line of sight to the nozzle and an unobstructed view of the print-in-progress for filming time lapses (I recommend my super-compact bed-mounted Raspi cam).
  5. Allow easy removal of the entire shroud assembly for access to the hot-end.

GUST is a work-in-progress, but it's ready to use right now! I suggest you 'Watch' this thing to get notifications about new revisions.

Important compatibility info

Known to fit:

  • Wanhao i3 Plus or rebadged versions
    • Stock hot-end/extruder
    • Micro Swiss all-metal hot-end
    • Does not fit Flexion hot-end/extruder (apparently the Flexion nozzle is too short?)
  • Monoprice Maker Select V2.1 (thanks, Roykinn7!)

This shroud is designed for a Wanhao i3 Plus, or a rebadged version of it. It fits onto an extruder bracket that has M3 holes shaped as slots spaced around 30 mm apart, on a tab that is 45 mm long.

There is a different kind of bracket that has holes (not slots) spaced 40 mm apart, on a tab that is 50 mm long. I have provided a slotted bracket to fit these measurements, but I can't guarantee that the other bracket dimensions are the same or that the shroud will fit your bracket's height.

I have also made the assumption that your nozzle is at least 6 mm tall from the heater block to the tip, which is the case for both the Plus' stock nozzle and also for the Micro Swiss all-metal hot-end's nozzle. GUST cannot fit into the space around a shorter nozzle, and cannot be made to fit there; it's already nearly too thin.

If you are able to use this shroud on a non-Plus model, could you please comment and let the community know? Info about your bracket and nozzle would be good.

Bill of Materials

Note: Always use the latest revision of each STL (e.g. use Rev 2 instead of Rev 1). The newest files are always listed first, and they are always compatible with each other; you can use the Rev 2 duct with the Rev 1 shroud, for example, as long as they are the latest revisions of those objects. The old files remain 'below the fold' in case you want to explore them.

  • 1× Cooling duct.stl. There is also a version with Meshmixer supports included, for those who don't have a slicer that can do custom supports.
  • 1× Bracket.stl. The slotted bracket can fit on brackets with both 30 and 40 mm screw hole distances, and allows you to adjust the shroud along the X axis.
  • (Optional) 1 mm shim.stl to raise the shroud above the tip of your nozzle. If you need a shim that is greater than 1 mm, use 10 mm shim.stl and tell the slicer to stop at the desired height. I use 3 mm of shim for my Micro Swiss hot end.
  • 1× 50×50×15 mm blower fan. 24 V for Plus machines, 12 V for standard machines.
  • 1× M4 screw (25 mm), washer, and nut.
  • 2× M3 screw (12 mm), washers, and nuts. I bonded wingnuts to grub screws with Loctite, and I use thumb wheels to tighten them down. Tool-less shroud removal!

Installation

  1. Level your bed.
  2. Join the blower fan, Duct, and Bracket using the M4 screw. Leave it loose for now.
  3. Attach Bracket to the fan mounting bracket of the extruder block using the M3 screws. Leave these loose for now.
  4. Looking from the side, align the nozzle with the opening of the shroud by moving the Bracket forwards or backwards. Tighten the M3 bracket screws.
  5. If needed, add Shims to raise the base of the shroud about 1 mm above the tip of the nozzle.
  6. Zero the Z axis. Pivot the Duct so that it is parallel to the bed. Confirm that it does not collide with the bed.
  7. Tighten the M4 screw.
  8. Suggested cooling profile: 0–20 % speed for the first layer. 100 % for all subsequent layers.

Test spike slicer settings

Want to follow along? Here are the settings I used:

  • PLA, 0.40 mm nozzle, 0.20 mm layer height.
  • 2 perimeters with 2 bottom layers
  • No infill
  • 75 mm/s base printing speed
  • Adjust printing speed for layers below 1 second, allow reduction down to 5 %

Frequently Asked Questions

Won't it melt from being so close to the nozzle?

Nope! My experience with shrouds like this is that so much cold air is passing through them that they barely deform, if at all. I have had this particular shroud printed in PLA and even touching the heater block's insulation and it isn't deformed.

If you are worried about the shroud melting while printing a large first layer without the fan running, there are four ways to deal with it:

  1. Trust that PLA has bad thermal conductivity, and the design of the shroud means that only an island on the top surface of the shroud is being heated up, and the heat will find it difficult to spread to the rest of the shroud to cause a structural failure.
  2. Increase the air gap between shroud and block.
  3. Put extra insulation between the shroud and heating block.
  4. Run the fan at a very low speed for the first layer (10-20 %) to keep air moving through it. Make sure to actually check that the fan turns at the speed you've selected; my fan won't turn for anything less than 20 % speed.

This was the best way to design the shroud as far as I could see, in order to meet the design requirement of getting right up against the nozzle. The nozzle is only 6 mm tall, so space is limited:

  | Heater block |
  ----------------
1 mm   |     | Insulating air gap
2 mm   |     | ===========
3 mm   |     | Air passage
4 mm   |     | Air passage
5 mm   |     | ===========
6 mm   \_____/ Clearance from print

There's no room, in short, and reducing the air passage just makes the fan louder and makes backflow worse.

What kind of blower fan should I use?

The strongest one you can find with the highest static pressure rating. You can always turn it down if it's too powerful. I've had good times with Shenzhen Gdstime Technology Co. Ltd fans. I've also heard good things about YYQ fans, although I have never used one. But caveat emptor: CFM specs from random sellers are probably untrue.

Can I use a 12 V fan in a 24 V system?

Yes, but you shouldn't. Aside from the possibility of the fans sparking because they're over-volted, they will eventually fail and start making these horrible grinding/rattling sounds.

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2 mm (0.40 mm nozzle)

Notes:

Print all objects as provided. Duct needs to be printed with support underneath the nozzle arm and underneath the top surface of the blower compartment. Do not add support to the interior. Duct is printed in this odd orientation because a) it's fastest, and b) it keeps the airway as smooth and clean as possible, which is crucial because the airway is so thin. If you cannot control how your slicer builds internal supports, Duct (with Meshmixer supports) is available.

Bracket and Shim should be printed with high infill and more perimeters (50 % infill and 3 perimeters?) so that you can really tighten those screws down.

Design rationale

I was unhappy with the fan shrouds currently available for the i3 family, so I made this one. After performing some in-depth experiments regarding part cooling, I came to several conclusions:

  1. Blower fans are the best fans to use for print cooling (reference).
  2. Shrouds that specifically direct air onto a narrow area are best for printing small features like spikes, which need to be cooled rapidly (reference).
  3. Shrouds that blow air over a large area are best for reducing overall warping (ref #2).
  4. If you can only use one fan shroud, you should use one that dumps air directly onto the plastic deposition area (ref. #2).
  5. Shrouds that completely surround the print area are not good (ref. #2, although it has been pointed out to me that the design of the 'Surround' shroud I tested is not particularly good).

This shroud is a synthesis of all of those ideas:

  1. It uses a blower fan to supply lots of high-pressure air directly to the printing area.
  2. Localised cooling at the nozzle helps small features cool down fast — the top 10 or so layers of the test spike are basically a single nozzle width, printed vertically into the air. This shroud cools it down fine, and it cools it evenly so that it's not blown over by the air pressure.
  3. I hypothesise that ring-type shrouds are bad because they trap hot air around the print. This design blows air from one side only, which means that hot air can get blown away.
Airflow validation

I tried to get software airflow simulation software working, but it either would not run or I couldn't learn it. I settled with printing just the output part of the duct and connecting it to a container that I held underneath a running tap. The movement of the water through the output gave me a rough idea of how the duct should function. I held the ducts upside down during testing so that the pattern of the flow would not be helped by gravity. I validated this method by running water through the venerable DiiiCooler and confirming that it did indeed create a 360° pattern of water.

2 Nov 2017 (rev. 3)

Cooling duct

  • Rev. 3 makes a minor change to the geometry of the nozzle which addresses some uneven cooling. I had designed the nozzle of Rev 2 to blow air directly under the nozzle, forgetting that most of that air would be occluded by the object that was being printed.

25 Oct 2017 (rev. 2)

Cooling duct

  • I suspected that Rev 1's output was not as multi-direction as I wanted to be, and I confirmed that this was the case by running water through the duct and observing the pattern.
  • Rev 2 has a new output pattern (inspired by DiiiCooler) that splits the flow of air and distributes it in a semi-circle around the included nozzle area. I tested this pattern by running water through it, and found the flow to be multi-directional as expected.
  • A redesign of the output's profile now directs the air lower down towards the plastic, whereas in Rev 1 it blew more onto the nozzle.
  • No other changes were made to any other STLs. Rev 0 and Rev 1 brackets and shims are compatible with the Rev 2 duct.

Meta

  • Uploaded Fusion 360 project files for Rev 2, and also for the output design sketches.

21 Oct 2017 (rev. 1)

Cooling duct

  • Air intake area is larger and curves more smoothly into the exhaust ducting.
  • Exhaust aperture now directs the air more downwards towards the print. Rev. 0 had the air mostly blowing across the nozzle instead of onto the plastic.
  • Removed the right face of the blower compartment to shorten print time, use less material, and reduce the reliance on internal supports. It can now be printed using supports from the print bed only, but you need to be able to cleanly bridge over about 20 mm.
  • Added a version of Cooling duct with pre-prepared tree supports from Meshmixer, for those who don't have Simplify3D.

Bracket

  • Extruder bracket mounts are now slots instead of holes.
  • Fan mount bracket extended to match the new reduced Cooling duct.
  • Fan mount hole is now a stepped slot. Users can choose the mounting hole that gets them closest to the desired height, and then fine-tune with shims.

Shim

  • Added 10 mm shim. Users can use it to make custom shim thicknesses by telling the slicer where to stop printing.

Meta

  • Uploaded Fusion 360 project file.
  • Added compatibility info.

19 Oct 2017 (rev. 0)

  • Initial release

description.text:
The FC mount can be printed in either flexi or solid filament but obviously flexi gives the FC added vibe damping.

The motor Dampners are also designed to be flexi but aernt essential for the build.

The FC of choice cannot use pinned connections as there's limited space under the canopy and direct wiring is just so much neater anyway

Any motor is usable upto 2205 in size (I originally planned to use 1806 but had the 2205's handy)

The Props I used are of a design that means they clear the top of the canopy, similar Tri's(such as DalDrops) or more common 2 blade props will strike the canopy unless a spacer is applied beneath the motors to lift them higher off the mounts.

The battery is the most restricted point in this design, obviously anything too big wont fit inside the removable battery bay and the bay itself is as large as the design allows without altering the design so much it no longer looks like a dji spark (which kinda defeats the whole point of the design really), I used a ZOP 850mah 70c which fits perfectly inside the bay.
The battery connector must be fixed in place once fitted (either hot glued or similar) to allow the bay to be slotted onto the frame and the battery terminals to mate without further fuss.
WARNING!:- incase the obvious didn't occur, you'll need a battery bay part for each battery!!

Hardware used :-

FC - Naze32 rev6 (direct soldered wiring, NO pins)
ESC - DYS 4in1 20A
MOTORS - Racerstar 2205 2300kv
PROPS - KingKong 5045 Tri's (with 5mm tip trimming)
RX - FRSky R6b (decased and unused pins removed)
BATTERY - ZOP Power 11.1V 850mah 70C 3S (size essential, no bigger dimensions)
FPV CAM - Eachine AIO TX03 (adapted from clover to whip antenna)

future add-ons/adaptions/revisions:-

Prop adapter to allow the use of genuine spark folding props (I already finished a design for 1806 motors but havnt perfected a version for 2205's like the racerstar with 5mm shafts yet)

Lower plate revision to allow the use of larger sized batteries without the use of the battery bay (no longer fully resembles a Spark but you can atleast opt to use higher cell (4s) and/or larger Mah Lipo's for greater flight time / Duration.

LED pods for the motor mounts (similar to the genuine spark), either fixed colour or utilizing the naze32's ability to control addressable LEDS and therefore display mode/battery status.

GPS!

Printer:

PolTur XL

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

50%

Notes:

28/10/2017:

added "battery adapter plate"

this adaption allows the use of larger sized lipos than the battery bay can accommodate, the only drawbacks being that the frame no longer appears entirely "spark like" and the original battery securing method can no longer be utilized, as an alternative a velcro lipo strap around the entire body and lipo works well (please see added pictures for example)

NB:I added a additional power supply lead to the DYS 20a 4in1 board that can be tucked away inside the main body when the spark-like battery bay lipos are in use and can then be taken out and used for larger lipo's when the adapter plate is in place (see photo's)

added "LED CAM mount"

5mm ultra bright LEDs that run off the same power feed as the AIO cam Ive used

CAM - Eachine TX03 switchable AIO cam (modified antenna from clover to whip concealed inside canopy)

LEDs - standard ultrabright 5mm resistored LEDs (suitable for use with either the 5v or 12v bec feed from the DYS board)

There is a second revision of this design now available (my own personal remix) which Ive named "the sparkie" as its still based generally on this design but allows a much larger selection of lipo sizes and has been given additional tilt to the motor arms which inturn allows for the use of more prop options and increases overall stability in the air.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2625982`

If your after a Dji spark lookalike clone then this design is for you.

If your after something with more options and the ability to go 4s/5s for some serious overpowered flight characteristics then Id use the Sparkie, I personally use the latter and can testify that this much power in such a small package is a absolute laugh a minute.

UPDATE: I just added version 2 (linear standoff mount v2). I changed the angle to be a little more upright and lined the holder up a bit more with the standoff. I find with the first version it gets in the way of the props easily if you don't have it lined up perfect. This new version makes that much less an issue as it gets the antenna up out of the way and lined up in the center better.

This is a standoff mount for your 5.8GHz linear antenna (also called whip antenna). After printing in a flexible filament like TPU, thread the antenna cable through the longer horizontal cylinder and press the antenna in. It should be a snug fit so the antenna doesn't pop out or move. It if it's snug, scale your print down a percent or two in the slicer and print again.

Then just slide the antenna over any standoff on your drone.

OpenForge
=========
Crenelated corridor tiles designed to be compatible with Dwarven Forge dungeon tiles. Can be stacked on Stone Corridor Tiles or Stone Wall Tiles with Pillars to create two sided defensive walls.
You can find this set on github
OpenForge Sets
=============
  • Smooth Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc.
  • Smooth Edge Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc. Edge tiles.
  • Stone Tile Series - Stone tiles.
  • Stone Edge Tile Series - Stone edge tiles.
  • Crenelated Tile Series - Crenelated Tiles
  • Crenelated Edge Tile Series - Crenelated edge tiles
  • Tudor Tile Series - Tudor tiles.
  • Tudor Edge Tile Series - Tudor edge tiles.
  • Ruined Series - Ruined stone walls
  • Accessories - Pillars, etc.
  • Non-Series Tiles - Misc tiles, such as the pool
  • Module Specific Tiles - Tiles designed for specific modules.
    • OpenForge is now a patron supported project. I use the resources that my patrons give me in order to get the resources to let me create more sophisticated tiles with a greater level of detail. Please, support me, and I’ll deliver an ongoing stream of awesome gaming terrain. You can find more about OpenForge and Masterwork Tools at our website, at our forums, or on twitter and facebook.
Painting

Painting was done in 5 layers.
  • Paint whole piece in black
  • Heavily dry brush with a dark grey
  • pick at least one other color (that could be stone) and paint some random stones, front and back.
  • dry brush with grey mixed with a little olive
  • lightly dry brush with a light grey, focusing most heavily on edges
    I paint the wall portion of the underside since it can be visible if the wall is stacked.

In this assignment, we were asked to work in pairs to collaborate and create a logo of our choice. We chose to create a 2D-3D model of the Barstool logo, a sports company that is very well known.

Our creation features 5 layers, each originally sketched then extruded. After extrusion, the pieces were filleted and compiled to create on smooth piece. The first layer composes the background which is a larger circle that circumscribes the entire image. The following layer is a more textured background with spikes to make the logo more visually appearing. Furthermore, the third layer contains a circular pattern of stars that circumscribe the barstool. On top of the star layer, there is a lightning bolt, and finally, the barstool itself appears on top of all the other layers. Each layer is extruded 0.1cm. In total, the thickness of the figure is 0.5 cm and it happens to fit just outside of a 5 cm x 5 cm square.

title: Prusa Z axis, the best AND the simplest !

description.text:
Owners of a Prusa Geeetech Al who have carried out all the mod I published here, mainly the Z axis, ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1830451, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2504861 ) are the proud owners of the best Prusa, no wobble, noise, vibration, fast, accurate AND simple.
See my other things (bearings, filament guide ...as they are used here).
But could it be made even simpler by getting rid of the Z smooth rods ?
"Good news everyone" (Professor Farnsworth) it can !
Indeed, the TR8 leadscrews are straight enough and can be used as guides too. The trick is to make Igus TR8 nuts with a perfect fit. Ball screws would do too but are far too expensive.
Note that TR8 are not as rigid as the 8mm smooth rods, TR10, TR12 would be better. Anyway the moving mass on X is about 250g. No that much vibration.

Sorry, I don't provide step by step instructions, no time for it. Most of it is explained in my previous things. Furthermore to implement this requires knowledge and skills that make these superfluous. Qualified people I am OK to help though.

comments.text: Nice idea, but perhaps a bit clumsy to forget the anti-backlash while removing the support rods. It might be low risk to some, to assume small mass won't create vibration, and a lead screw should be sufficient. Have you considered acceleration and jerk? Lead screw dynamics and harmonic vibration under load? This is an extruded form of the logo of Barstool Sports, a satirical sports blog, that fits in a square about 5 cm x 5 cm x .5 cm rectangular prism.
This consists of 5 layers, one for the barstool, one for a lightning bolt and initials, one for the circle of stars, one for a spiked circle in the background, and finally, one for the circle in the background that protects the edges of the stars from tearing or coming off.
The barstool, stars, and initials are filleted to smooth of the sharp edges.. Lastly, the edge of the lowest circle is chamfered.

Post-printing comments:
Please note that some details may be too fine for the printer to print. With the limitations of the printer to print with a certain extruder radius, it may be unable to print out the stars or the initials correctly. The initials and stars may be slightly cut off, miss some of the filleted details, or not be as accurate as the simulated model. Also, the picture used in the cover photo is not of this model as the original is nowhere to be found. There are some differences between the model such as the different initials and the fact that my model has an un-merged base, meaning that it could split from the rest of the design. For these reasons, I strongly urge you to print out the figure at at least 150% scale for better details on the print and get some glue ready in case the base of the figure does not stick together with the rest.

This was created with my partner Darren LePage for coordination and collaboration.

Problem Statement:

With a partner, you will design a “2D” placard using Solidworks. You and your partner will have the same design which meets the constraints below, and you will EACH use Solidworks to create your design.

Constraints:

Should have a flat back; detail will be on the front side
Should fit inside a box that is 25cm2 when lying flat
Should be no more than 1cm thick
Detail will be made using sketches that are extruded to different heights
Sketch must begin with a constraint box, a center-rectangle created from the origin)
Dimensions should be detailed but efficient
Sketch must contain zero error messages
Sketch must be fully defined when complete
Demonstrate efficient use of “Construction Lines”/”Reference Geometry”
Demonstrate efficient use of “Offset Entities”
Demonstrate efficient use of “Manual Relations”
Demonstrate efficient use of “Smart Dimensions”
Demonstrate efficient use of “Mirroring”
Demonstrate efficient use of “Linear Patterns”

Make constraint box for entire image that is centered on the origin
Make constraint box from top right corner of the first box dimensioned to printed out photo (4.6 cm x 4.75 cm)
Create stars
-Mark center point from left and top side of big constraint box and make construction circle
around it
-Split up circle into arcs measure 72° starting from leftmost point (horizontal from origin).
-Make construction line from leftmost point as the horizontal diameter
-Create converging lines from the adjacent points and set them as equal with a set length
Mirror the converging lines across the diameter construction line
-Use a circular sketch pattern to copy the star around the origin so that there are 24 stars

Build the lightning bolt behind the stool
-Plot each corner point on the bolt with a set dimension away from sides of the smaller
constraint box from x and y axes
-Connect the adjacent points with lines

Create bar stool
-Create new sketch to build left side of the bar stool using the line tool and basic drawing
tools.
-Create a reference line on the center of the smaller constraint box at a set angle with
infinite length
-Create a parallel line to the left of the reference line that is dimensioned away from the
sides of the small constraint box with a set length
-Create another reference line to the left of the reference line with s et length with endpoints
dimensioned away from the sides of the smaller constraint box
-Offset this bi-directionally
-Connect the endpoints on the bottom of these lines with a 3-point arc with the midpoint
dimensioned away from the bottom of the reference line they are offsetted around
-Mirror the parallel line from the first reference line and the lines and arc just made about
the first tilted reference line
-Create a perpendicular reference line from the tilted reference line that converges on the
endpoints of the lines parallel to the reference line
-Create a point that is on the intersection of this line and the tilted reference line
-Create a 3-point arc that is connected to bottom endpoints of the parallel lines to the tilted
reference line and dimension the vertex away from the last point
-Create an ellipse centered on the reference line that is dimensioned away from the
intersection of the reference line and the top of the box
-Make a reference line that converges at the farthest left and right points of the ellipse that
is perpendicular to the tilted reference line and has a midpoint on it
-Dimension the endpoints of the last reference line
-Place points on the intersections of the ellipse and the first reference line and dimension
them away from each other
-Offset the ellipse on the outside a set distance and set it for construction
-Create lines that start from the endpoints of the reference line and end on the offset under
the seat that are parallel to the first tilted reference line
-Use 3 point arcs in the place of the reference offset on the sections where it is open to the
left of the first tilted reference line and dimension it so that it is as close to the offset as
possible
-Mirror these arcs over the tilted reference line
-Create a 3-point arc for construction that converges on the reference lines on both sides of
the first tilted reference line with endpoints dimensioned away from the bottom of those
reference lines
-Dimension the vertex of the arc away from the point that the arc on the bottom of the
middle leg is dimensioned off of
-Create a reference line that connects the endpoints of the arc
-Mirror the arc over the reference line
-Offset the arcs a set distance bi-directionally

Background: Create spiked circle
-Create reference circle centered on the origin with a diameter of 5 cm
-Create a non-reference circle inside with diameter of 4 cm
-Create reference circle from that center with diameter of 4.5 cm
-Create a horizontal reference line on the center of the circles and have it go for an infinite
length
-Make lines connecting the 4 cm circle to the intersection of the reference line and
the outside reference circle that are 15º from the reference line
-Use circular sketch pattern so that there are four of these all around
-Make lines connecting the 4 cm circle to the intersection of the reference line and
the 4.5 cm reference circle that are 15º from the reference line
-Use a circular sketch pattern so that there are 24 of these figures connected to each other
about the center of the circles

Create Background Circle
-Create new sketch
-Place circle centered around the center of the spiked circle and dimension it

Extrude Everything
-Extrude the barstool up .5 cm
-Extrude the stars up .3 cm
-Extrude the lightning bolt and initials .4 cm
-Extrude the spiked circle .2 cm
-Extrude last background circle .1 cm

Use text tool and add initials to the face.
-Extrude these letters 0.1 cm from the face which it is on.
-Fillet the face of the letters and the bottom of the letters to the surface that they are on.

Apply Fillets
-Apply face fillet to the front of the barstool.
-Apply a face fillet to each star. Some stars may be difficult to select and fillet, but for those
select the edges individually and fillet them one by one.
-Apply chamfer to the bottom background circle

This is a 2D/D model of a PAC-man inspired plaque. PAC-man is an arcade game developed by NAMCO. The plaque features the main character, PAC-man, ghosts and from Ms. PAC-man, Ms. PAC-man. The game was first released in Japan in 1980. The model fits within a 12.5cm by 3.4cm construction box. It features 5 extruded layers. The first layer is the base layer that is 0.2cm thick. The second layer consists only of the pupils that are extruded to 0.3cm from the bottom.The third layer is 0.4cm thick and consists of the words "PAC-MAN", PAC-Man's body, Ms.PAC-man's body, the ghost's bodies, the barriers, the dots and pellets. The next layer is just the middle of Ms. PAC-man's bow and is extruded to be 0.5 cm. The final layer consists of the loops of Ms. PAC-man's bow and is extruded to 0.6cm from the base.

This project was created in conjunction with awolfert2018.

Print Size

As you can tell in the photo, printing at the scale of the original STL will not allow the detail in the sketch to be fully expressed. Areas such as the dots and the pellets were too small to be printed well. It caused some spaghetti to occur.

If you are planning to print this piece, I suggest that you print it at least 150% of the original STL file.
